  "prompt": "What is the best budget camera phone?",
  "response": "Okay, the \"best\" budget camera phone is subjective and depends on your specific needs and priorities. However, I can give you some top recommendations based on different criteria within the budget category (let's assume \"budget\" means under $300, although you can find good options even cheaper):\n\n**Overall Best for Camera Quality (Considering Price):**\n\n*   **Google Pixel 6a (Often found on sale):** This is often cited as the king of budget phone cameras, specifically the main camera. It punches *way* above its weight class thanks to Google's excellent computational photography.\n    *   **Pros:** Amazing image processing, particularly in daylight and low light, great dynamic range, clean details, accurate colors.  Often gets software updates for a long time.\n    *   **Cons:**  Older processor (Tensor G1, still good), screen isn't the brightest, charging speed is relatively slow. Ultra-wide not quite as good as the main sensor.\n\n**Alternatives to the Pixel 6a (depending on price fluctuations and availability):**\n\n*   **Samsung Galaxy A54 5G:** Samsung often has great deals and the A54 is a very capable phone with a good main camera, decent ultrawide, and macro lens.\n    *   **Pros:** Versatile camera system, good display, water resistance, great battery life.\n    *   **Cons:** Processing can be a bit over-saturated for some, not as good in low light as the Pixel.\n\n**Best for Video:**\n\n*   **Generally, the phones good for photos are also decent for video, but look for features like:**\n    *   **Optical Image Stabilization (OIS):** Helps stabilize footage, especially in lower light or when moving.\n    *   **Good Stabilization Software:** Many phones use electronic image stabilization (EIS) alongside OIS.\n    *   **4K Recording:**  Pretty standard now, but ensure it's available on all cameras you might use.\n    *   **Good Dynamic Range:** Prevents blown-out highlights or crushed shadows in video.\n\n**Important Considerations When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Camera Specs Aren't Everything:** Megapixels don't tell the whole story. The size of the sensor, the quality of the lens, and, most importantly, the image processing software are crucial.\n*   **Read Reviews and Compare:** Don't just rely on specs. Look at sample photos and videos from various phones to see which ones produce the kind of images you like. Sites like GSMArena, DxOMark (take with a grain of salt), and YouTube are your friends.\n*   **Consider Your Needs:** Do you prioritize low-light performance, zoom capabilities, a wide-angle lens, or selfie quality?\n*   **Check for Deals and Refurbished Options:** You can often find last year's flagship phones at budget prices.  Certified refurbished phones can be an excellent way to save money.\n*   **Software Support:**  How long will the phone receive software updates and security patches?  Google and Samsung are generally better at this than other brands.\n\n**To give you the BEST specific recommendation, I need a little more information:**\n\n*   **What is your absolute maximum budget?**\n*   **What are your priorities in a camera phone?** (e.g., low light, zoom, selfies, video)\n*   **What country are you in?** (Pricing and availability vary greatly).\n\nOnce you provide this, I can give you a more tailored recommendation!\n",
